{"body":"## Problem

\`sequant_run\` can take up to 30 minutes. Currently the MCP client has no visibility into progress during execution — the only option is polling \`sequant_status\` from a separate tool call. This creates two problems:

1. **Timeout risk:** MCP clients have default timeouts (typically 60-120s). Without progress notifications, the \`tools/call\` request will timeout well before \`sequant_run\` completes. The MCP SDK's \`resetTimeoutOnProgress: true\` option automatically extends the timeout when progress notifications are received — but only if the server sends them.

2. **Poor UX:** The LLM has to interleave \`sequant_status\` polling between turns, which is awkward and uses extra tool calls. Progress notifications are pushed server-to-client during the call, giving real-time visibility without polling.

### How MCP progress works

The client sends a \`progressToken\` in \`_meta\` when calling a tool. The server emits \`notifications/progress\` during execution. The SDK automatically resets the client-side timeout on each notification.

```typescript
// Client side (handled by SDK)
const result = await client.callTool(
  { name: "sequant_run", arguments: { issues: [123] } },
  { resetTimeoutOnProgress: true, maxTotalTimeout: 1800_000 }
);

// Server side
if (progressToken !== undefined) {
  await server.server.notification({
    method: "notifications/progress",
    params: { progress: 2, total: 6, progressToken, message: "Issue #123: exec phase started" }
  });
}
```

### Current workaround

Poll \`sequant_status\` every 5-10 seconds. This works but requires the LLM to manage polling loops and wastes tool calls.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] **AC-1:** \`sequant_run\` reads \`progressToken\` from \`extra._meta?.progressToken\`
- [ ] **AC-2:** When \`progressToken\` is present, phase transitions emit \`notifications/progress\` with: phase name, issue number, human-readable message
- [ ] **AC-3:** Progress \`total\` is calculated from issue count × phase count (e.g., 2 issues × 3 phases = 6 steps)
- [ ] **AC-4:** Progress notifications are skipped when no \`progressToken\` is provided (backward compatible)
- [ ] **AC-5:** Existing tests pass; add test for progress emission when token is provided

## Design

### Where to emit

The \`sequant_run\` tool handler already parses stdout from the CLI subprocess for structured output. Phase transitions can be detected from the subprocess output and mapped to progress notifications:

```typescript
// In the sequant_run handler
let currentStep = 0;
const totalSteps = issues.length * phaseList.length;

// On each phase transition detected from subprocess output
if (progressToken !== undefined) {
  currentStep++;
  await server.server.notification(
    {
      method: "notifications/progress",
      params: {
        progress: currentStep,
        total: totalSteps,
        progressToken,
        message: \`Issue #\${issueNumber}: \${phase} phase \${status}\`,
      },
    },
    { relatedRequestId: extra.requestId },
  );
}
```

### Progress granularity

| Event | Message format | Progress increment |
|-------|---------------|-------------------|
| Issue started | "Issue #123: starting" | +0 (no increment) |
| Phase started | "Issue #123: spec phase started" | +1 |
| Phase completed | "Issue #123: spec phase completed" | +0 (start of next phase increments) |
| Issue completed | "Issue #123: completed (passed)" | +0 (final phase start already incremented) |

### Detecting phase transitions

The CLI subprocess writes to stdout/stderr. Options:
1. **Parse stderr for phase markers** — the CLI already logs phase transitions
2. **Read state file periodically** — poll \`.sequant/state.json\` for phase changes
3. **Structured progress output** — add a \`--progress-json\` flag to the CLI that emits JSON progress lines

Option 1 is simplest and matches current architecture. Options 2-3 are more reliable but add complexity.

## Files in Scope

- \`src/mcp/tools/run.ts\` — add progress notification emission
- \`src/mcp/server.ts\` — may need to expose server instance for \`notification()\` calls

## References

- [MCP Progress spec](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/specification/2025-03-26/basic/utilities/progress)
- [MCP SDK \`resetTimeoutOnProgress\`](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/typescript-sdk/blob/main/docs/client.md) — client timeout management
- [Everything server: trigger-long-running-operation](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/servers/tree/main/src/everything) — reference implementation

## Non-goals

- Changing the polling pattern for \`sequant_status\` — it still works and is useful independently
- Client-side progress display — handled by the MCP client automatically","labels":[{"id":"LA_kwDOQzPeLM8AAAACT-M2TQ","name":"enhancement","description":"New feature or request","color":"a2eeef"},{"id":"LA_kwDOQzPeLM8AAAACUl1BaQ","name":"planned","description":"Implementation plan approved","color":"0E8A16"},{"id":"LA_kwDOQzPeLM8AAAACVOX0xg","name":"cli","description":"CLI commands and interface","color":"5319E7"}],"state":"OPEN","title":"MCP server: add progress notifications for sequant_run"}

